05492nam a22009495i 9780812298529DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780812298529  a(DE-B1597)627971  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aTR15b.M666 2022 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a770223/eng/202205231 aMorris-Reich, Amos, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhotography and Jewish History :bFive Twentieth-Century Cases /cAmos Morris-Reich. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Utopia and Photography circa 1900: Albert Kahn and the Archives of the Planet -- tChapter 2. The Boundaries of Photographic Intention: Helmar Lerski’s “Failed” Project -- tChapter 3. Album of an Extinct Race: Eugen Fischer and Photography -- tChapter 4. Photography for Its Own Sake: Robert Frank and The Americans -- tChapter 5. Photography and Rupture: S. An-sky, Solomon Yudovin, and the Documentation of Russian Jewry -- tConclusion. Photography and Democracy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is a sign of the accepted evidentiary status of photographs that historians regularly append them to their accounts, Amos Morris-Reich observes. Very often, however, these photographs are treated as mere illustrations, simple documentations of the events that transpired. Scholars of photography, on the other hand, tend to prioritize the photographs themselves, relegating the historical contexts to the background. For Morris-Reich, however, photography exists within reality; it partakes in and is very much a component of the history it records. Morris-Reich examines how photography affects categories of history and experience, how it is influenced by them, and the ways in which our understanding of the relationship between history and photography can be theorized and reoriented.Morris-Reich here turns to five twentieth-century cases in which photography and Jewish history intersect: Albert Kahn’s utopian attempt to establish a photographic archive in Paris in order to advance world peace; the spectacular failed project of Helmar Lerski, the most prominent photographer in British Mandate Jewish Palestine; photography in the long career of Eugen Fischer, a Nazi professor of genetics; the street photography of Robert Frank; and the first attempt to introduce photography into the study of Russian Jewry prior to World War I, as seen from the post-Holocaust perspective of the early twenty-first century. Illustrated with nearly 100 images, Photography and Jewish History moves beyond a focus on Jewish photographers or the photographic representation of Jews or Jewish visibility to plumb the deeper and more significant registers of twentieth-century Jewish political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHistoriography and photography. 0aJewsxHistoriography. 0aJewsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxPhilosophy. 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspects. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspects. 4aArts-Photography. 4aHistory of Jewish People and Culture. 4aInterdisciplinary-Jewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAlbert Kahn.  aAn-Sky.  aBritish Palestine.  aEugen Fischer.  aHelmar Lerski.  aJewish identity and photography.  aJudaism.  aRobert Frank.  aRussian Jewry.  aSolomon Yudovin.  aUtopia.  aVilem Flusser.  aZionism.  adocumentary.  aessentialist.  aholocaust.  arepresentation.  ascientific racism.  atheor